3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates based on the premium/discount between perpetual price and oracle price, settled every hour instead of the typical 8-hour cycle. The platform uses GLP/GM liquidity pools as counterparties, meaning funding flows between traders and the liquidity pool. Oracle dependency creates unique rate dynamics compared to order book exchanges, as rates reflect oracle premium rather than order book imbalances."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","FET","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FET represents AI infrastructure with mid-tier volume, generating moderate funding rate volatility suitable for arbitrage strategies. The hourly settlement frequency on GMX provides more frequent capture opportunities compared to 8-hour cycles elsewhere. AI narrative tokens like FET often experience sustained directional bias, creating predictable funding rate patterns."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FET/USDT on GMX typically exhibits higher funding rate volatility during AI narrative cycles and market volatility spikes. The hourly settlement creates smoother rate progression compared to traditional 8-hour cycles, reducing sudden rate shocks. During AI sector rallies, FET often maintains positive funding rates for extended periods due to long bias, while bear markets see more balanced or negative rates. Oracle-based pricing can create temporary disconnects from spot markets, generating brief arbitrage windows."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between GMX and centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX often emerges due to oracle lag and different rate calculation methods. The hourly funding cycle allows for more precise entry/exit timing compared to 8-hour settlements elsewhere. GMX's higher trading fees (0.05%/0.07%) must be factored against funding rate differentials, typically requiring rate spreads above 0.2% hourly to remain profitable. Price impact on larger positions can affect arbitrage viability due to GMX's liquidity pool mechanism."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency creates smart contract risk and potential price manipulation vectors not present in order book exchanges. GMX's battle-tested track record since 2021 provides confidence, but Chainlink oracle failures could impact position management. Arbitrum network congestion can affect transaction timing, potentially missing optimal funding captures during volatile periods. The platform's higher fees compared to centralized exchanges require careful calculation of net arbitrage returns, especially for smaller position sizes."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does GMX's hourly funding settlement affect FET arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Hourly settlements provide more frequent capture opportunities and smoother rate transitions compared to 8-hour cycles. This allows for more precise position management and reduces the risk of adverse rate movements between settlements."},{"question":"What makes FET funding rates unique on GMX compared to centralized exchanges?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracles for price discovery rather than order book dynamics, creating different rate calculation mechanics. This often results in temporary rate divergences from CEX platforms, especially during volatile AI sector movements."},{"question":"What are the minimum rate spreads needed for profitable FET arbitrage on GMX?","answer":"Due to GMX's 0.05%/0.07% trading fees, rate spreads typically need to exceed 0.2% hourly to cover costs and generate profit. This threshold increases with position size due to price impact considerations in GMX's liquidity pool model."},{"question":"How does GMX's oracle dependency impact FET funding rate reliability?","answer":"Oracle-based pricing creates more stable rate calculations but introduces smart contract and oracle manipulation risks. Chainlink's proven reliability for FET price feeds provides confidence, though traders should monitor oracle health and potential latency during extreme volatility."}]}]
